  "prompt": "What is the maximum number of tabs open in Google or Computer?",
  "response": "The maximum number of tabs you can open in a web browser like Google Chrome isn't set to a specific number but is generally limited by your computer's hardware, particularly its RAM (Random Access Memory) and to some extent the processing power. In practical terms, you can keep opening tabs until your system's performance degrades to the point of being unusable or the browser itself crashes.\n\nMost modern computers can handle dozens to even hundreds of open tabs, assuming there are no excessively demanding processes on the pages. However, the actual number can vary significantly based on the complexity of the web pages you're opening (e.g., pages with multimedia content or scripts running in the background) and the overall capabilities of your computer. Additionally, both browser and system stability can be influenced by the operating system and the version of the browser you're using.\n\nSome browsers might also have configurable limits or extensions that can help manage the number of open tabs, but by default, there generally isn't a hard cap imposed by the browsers themselves.",
